  <h6 id="s1e1">1. Sins of the Past</h6>
  <p> Ah, the first episode. The show starts out, if you can remember back this far, with Xena on a repentance mission to lay down her weapons and start over. This is a theme that is embedded into the core of the show. It is explored again most explicitly in <a href="#s2e2">Remember Nothing</a> and somewhat in <a href="#">Chakram</a>, episodes that span nearly the entire show. It is impressive, I think, that the very first visaul the show evokes is one so integral to the core issues the show grapples with thoughout its existence and evolution. This is also the storyline that is most readily associated with the other main character, Gabrielle, as she grapples with first blood innocence (see <a href="#">"Dreamworker"</a>, <a href="#">"The Deliverer"</a>) and then with the deep moral greyness of fighting for good versus reverence for all life (see all of <a href="#">season 4</a>). However, lesser-seen is the battle Xena fights with this. While it is usually cast in the light of attonment and duty (see the whole show, but in particular <a href="#">"Intimate Stranger"</a>, <a href="#">"A Good Day"</a>, <a href="#">"Forgiven"</a>, and <a href="#">"The Way"</a>), Xena started her post-Warlord journey with abandoning the sword, and this is a notable theme throughout the show as well.</p>
