  <h6 id="s2e2">2. Remember Nothing</h6>
  <p>This is one of those Xena episodes that throws you for a loop into a place that is both relatively independent of the season arc, and yet somehow also extremely integral to the canon of the show. This episode is foundational to illustrating Xena's history as a person, and the first episode that really takes on the question "What would the world look like if Xena hadn't done what she did?" As I have discussed many times in the past, one core throughline of this show is grappling with the difficult territory of the morality of battle and taking lives. This episode's salient messages are full of complexity and apparent contradiction: the plot is driven by Xena's remorse at killing a boy in the heat of battle, yet the main takeaway is that Xena's existence has saved the world from a terrible fate, and furthermore, she chooses to leave that alternate world because of Gabrielle losing her blood innocence. In typical Xena fashion, the show does not shy away from this ambiguity. The show paints a picture of a world in which the only choice seems to be to fight, but in which killing is a terrible price for both the warrior's psyche and the inherent deep immorality of ending life. No resoultion is found.</p>

